🛠️ **Setting Up Ollama (Local AI)**
Ollama is the engine that allows you to run Large Language Models directly on your local machine. Follow these steps to get it installed and running.

Step 1: Install Ollama
You can install Ollama using your terminal or command prompt. Choose the command for your operating system:

For macOS:
Open your Terminal and paste the following command:

``Bash
curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh
(Alternatively, you can download the standard Mac installer from ollama.com/download)

For Windows:
Open PowerShell and run:

PowerShell
irm https://ollama.com/install.ps1 | iex
(Alternatively, download the Windows .exe installer directly from ollama.com/download)

Step 2: Verify the Installation
Once installed, make sure Ollama is working and check the current version. Open your terminal and run:

Bash
ollama --version
You should see an output like: ollama version is 0.x.x

Step 3: Install and Run a Model
With Ollama, installing and running a model happens in a single command. If you don't have the model yet, Ollama will automatically download it first and then start an interactive chat session.

To install and run the model, use the run command:

Bash
ollama run kimi k2:cloud
Note: Depending on your internet speed and the model's size, the initial download may take a few minutes. Once it says "success," you can start typing your prompts directly in the terminal!

Step 4: Check Your Installed Models
To see a list of all the models currently downloaded to your hard drive, along with their file sizes, use the ls (list) command:

``bash
  ollama ls
Step 5: Remove a Model to Free Up Space
LLMs can take up a lot of storage space. If you are done testing a model and want to reclaim your hard drive space, use the rm (remove) command followed by the model name:

Bash
ollama rm kimi k2:cloud
